Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: While the original "Calibrate-to-Learn, Learn-to-Calibrate" (CLLC) framework presents a compelling bidirectional integration of few-shot learning and calibration via a meta-calibrator, it treats calibration as an auxiliary correction applied *after* or *alongside* adaptation. Drawing inspiration from Papers 1–3—particularly their insights on how training dynamics affect calibration and the need for graded correctness in complex outputs—I propose a more radical shift: embedding calibration directly into the few-shot learning *objective* itself, not just as a post-hoc refinement but as a co-optimized, differentiable component of model updating. The key insight is that miscalibration in low-resource languages stems not only from poor confidence scaling but from misaligned gradient signals during rapid adaptation. Standard few-shot fine-tuning can overfit to spurious patterns in small support sets, especially in typologically distant languages, leading to high-confidence errors. Instead of correcting this *afterward*, we should shape the adaptation process to favor updates that are both accurate *and* reliably confident. My new idea introduces **Gradient-Aware Calibration Regularization (GACR)**, a method that injects a calibration-aware loss into the inner loop of few-shot learning, penalizing parameter updates that increase predictive confidence without proportional gains in correctness. This is achieved by dynamically estimating calibration error (e.g., ECE) over the support set during adaptation and backpropagating through this metric to regularize gradients. Crucially, GACR uses a **language-adaptive uncertainty prior**, derived from linguistic metadata and precomputed calibration baselines across languages, to modulate the strength of regularization—applying stronger constraints where models are historically prone to overconfidence (e.g., low-resource, non-Latin script languages). Unlike static calibration or post-hoc meta-calibrators, GACR makes reliability an intrinsic part of learning, enabling the model to “learn calibratability” during adaptation. Furthermore, I extend evaluation beyond classification to include long-form generation tasks (e.g., multilingual summarization), incorporating partial correctness via distributional calibration metrics inspired by Paper 3. This transforms calibration from a downstream fix into a foundational mechanism for trustworthy multilingual generalization.

