  "Idea": "We propose a paradigm shift in the adaptation of Massively Multilingual Language Models (MMLMs): integrating calibration as a core, differentiable component of few-shot learning through Gradient-Aware Calibration Regularization (GACR). Rather than treating calibration as a separate post-processing step or auxiliary network, GACR embeds a dynamic calibration loss directly into the inner-loop optimization of few-shot adaptation, ensuring that parameter updates do not merely maximize accuracy but also preserve or improve confidence reliability. Specifically, during each few-shot episode, we compute a differentiable approximation of Expected Calibration Error (ECE) over the model’s support set predictions and combine it with the standard cross-entropy loss using a language-specific adaptive weight. This weight is determined by a lightweight calibration sensitivity function that considers typological distance from English, token frequency, script type, and historical miscalibration trends observed in zero-shot settings. By backpropagating through the ECE term, GACR discourages sharp confidence increases unless matched by actual performance gains—effectively preventing overconfident overfitting on small, noisy few-shot sets. To handle languages with minimal supervision, we further introduce a meta-learning stage where the calibration sensitivity function is optimized across diverse language episodes to generalize to unseen low-resource cases. We extend our framework to long-form generation tasks (e.g., multilingual summarization, open-ended QA) by adopting a distributional calibration approach: instead of binary correctness, we use semantic similarity scores (e.g., BERTScore) between predicted and reference outputs to define graded correctness, then align model confidence (e.g., average token entropy or self-rated certainty) with this continuous correctness distribution. This enables calibration assessment even when responses are partially correct—a critical ad